msgid ""
"The guiding principle: move frequently accessed data into faster, closer "
"memory. Registers are fastest but per-thread; shared memory is fast and "
"visible to the whole block; global memory is large but slow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:34
msgid ""
"The CUDA memory hierarchy from fastest (registers, per-thread) to largest "
"(global DRAM, all threads). Each tier trades capacity for latency. The right "
"panel shows scope and the cuda-oxide API for each level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:39
msgid "Contexts and streams"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:41
msgid ""
"Before diving into memory APIs, two host-side concepts that appear in every "
"code example need introduction: **contexts** and **streams**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:44
msgid ""
"A **CUDA context** (`CudaContext`) binds the host thread to a specific GPU. "
"It owns all resources on that device -- modules, streams, allocations. You "
"typically create one at the start of your program:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:48
msgid ""
"use cuda_core::CudaContext;\n"
"\n"
"let ctx = CudaContext::new(0).unwrap();   // bind to GPU 0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:54
msgid ""
"A **CUDA stream** (`CudaStream`) is an ordered queue of GPU operations. "
"Operations enqueued on the **same** stream execute in FIFO order -- each one "
"sees all side effects of the preceding operations. Operations on "
"**different** streams may overlap and run concurrently with no ordering "
"guarantees between them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:60
msgid ""
"let stream = ctx.default_stream();     // the implicit, always-available "
"stream\n"
"let work_stream = stream.fork()?;      // a new stream, joined to the "
"parent's current position\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:65
msgid ""
"Every memory transfer and kernel launch requires a stream. For single-stream "
"programs (which covers most examples in this book), the **default stream** "
"is all you need -- everything is sequential and correct by construction. "
"Multi-stream pipelines unlock overlap between compute and data movement, but "
"require explicit synchronization via events or `join`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:71
msgid ""
"Same stream:       [kernel_A] → [memcpy_B] → [kernel_C]     (automatic "
"ordering)\n"
"Different streams: [kernel_A on stream 1] | [memcpy_B on stream 2]  "
"(concurrent, needs events)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:80
msgid ""
"Top: single-stream execution where operations are automatically ordered in "
"FIFO. Bottom: multi-stream execution where streams A and B run concurrently, "
"with an event establishing the data dependency between kernel_write and "
"kernel_read."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:86
msgid ""
"The [Launching Kernels](launching-kernels.md) chapter covers stream usage in "
"launch macros, and the [Async GPU Programming](../async-programming/the-"
"device-operation-model.md) section covers `DeviceOperation` which manages "
"streams automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:91
msgid "`DeviceBuffer` -- host/device transfers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:93
msgid ""
"`DeviceBuffer<T>` in `cuda_core` is the primary way to allocate device "
"memory and move data between host and GPU:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:96
msgid ""
"use cuda_core::{CudaContext, DeviceBuffer};\n"
"\n"
"let ctx = CudaContext::new(0).unwrap();\n"
"let stream = ctx.default_stream();\n"
"\n"
"// Host → device: copy a host slice to GPU memory\n"
"let a_dev = DeviceBuffer::from_host(&stream, &host_data).unwrap();\n"
"\n"
"// Allocate zeroed device memory\n"
"let mut c_dev = DeviceBuffer::<f32>::zeroed(&stream, 1024).unwrap();\n"
"\n"
"// Device → host: read results back\n"
"let results = c_dev.to_host_vec(&stream).unwrap();\n"
msgstr ""

