#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:196
msgid ""
"This is why typed `#[cuda_module]` methods accept `&DeviceBuffer<T>` for "
"`&[T]` and `&mut DeviceBuffer<T>` for writable slice-like parameters. The "
"generated method extracts the pointer and length for you. Inside the kernel, "
"the compiler reconstitutes the slice struct from the scalar parameters, so "
"your kernel code sees normal `&[T]` types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:206
msgid ""
"Argument scalarization: the host passes Rust slices as (ptr, len) pairs "
"through the ABI boundary. The device kernel receives flat scalar parameters "
"and the compiler reconstitutes the original Rust types inside the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:212
msgid ""
"Scalarization is completely invisible in normal kernel code. You write "
"`&[f32]` in the signature and use it as a regular slice. The generated "
"launch method and the compiler handle everything else."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:217
msgid "`DisjointSlice` -- safe parallel writes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:219
msgid ""
"In CUDA C++, the standard pattern for parallel output is a raw `__global__` "
"pointer that every thread indexes into. This is inherently unsafe -- nothing "
"prevents two threads from writing to the same location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:223
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide provides `DisjointSlice<T, IndexSpace>` as a safe alternative. It "
"wraps a mutable slice and only allows writes through a `ThreadIndex` whose "
"`IndexSpace` matches its own. Combined with matching prepared launch "
"geometry, this ensures each thread accesses a unique element:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:228
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, DisjointSlice};\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn double(input: &[f32], mut out: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    if let Some((out_elem, idx)) = out.get_mut_indexed() {\n"
"        *out_elem = input[idx.get()] * 2.0;\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:239
msgid ""
"`get_mut_indexed()` is the one-call form: it mints the per-thread witness "
"and resolves it to a `&mut T` in a single shot. `None` covers both out-of-"
"grid threads (e.g. `col >= ROW_STRIDE` for 2D) and out-of-slice indices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:243
msgid ""
"The explicit two-step form `let idx = thread::index_1d(); out.get_mut(idx)` "
"is also available when you need the index for parallel arithmetic across "
"multiple slices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:246
msgid ""
"For patterns like reductions where multiple threads intentionally write to "
"the same location, `get_unchecked_mut` (unsafe) provides an escape hatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:250
msgid "Why `ThreadIndex` makes this safe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:252
msgid ""
"The key to `DisjointSlice`'s safety is `ThreadIndex<'kernel, IndexSpace>` -- "
"an opaque witness with no public constructor. The only way to obtain one is "
"through trusted index functions that derive the value from hardware built-in "
"variables (`threadIdx`, `blockIdx`, `blockDim`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:257
msgid ""
"let idx = thread::index_1d();          // ThreadIndex<'_, Index1D> -- ok\n"
"let bad = ThreadIndex::new(42);        // does not exist -- private "
"constructor\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:262
msgid ""
"This works because CUDA's thread indices are **uniform values provided by "
"the hardware**: every thread in a block receives a unique `threadIdx` from "
"the GPU's warp scheduler. For 1D grid launches (where only the x dimension "
"is used), the global index derived from `blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx."
"x` is unique across the entire grid."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:268
msgid ""
"That last statement is conditional: `index_1d()` ignores Y and Z. A 2D grid "
"would repeat the same X-derived index for every Y coordinate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:271
msgid ""
"PreparedLaunch(domain=1) -> Y/Z inactive -> safe DisjointSlice writes\n"
"raw LaunchConfig         -> caller proves Y/Z inactive -> unsafe launch\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:276
msgid ""
"The witness proves the device-side index space; the prepared launch proves "
"the host-side geometry. Both are needed for a fully safe launch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:279
msgid ""
"The witness is also `!Send + !Sync + !Copy + !Clone`, and its `'kernel` "
"lifetime is borrowed from a stack-local scope the macros inject -- so a "
"thread can't park its `ThreadIndex` in shared memory for a neighbour to pick "
"up later, and the witness can't outlive the kernel body. Combine that with "
"the `IndexSpace` parameter (`Index1D`, `Index2D<S>`, `Runtime2DIndex`) and "
"the type system rejects mismatched 2D strides at compile time too -- a data-"
"race hazard becomes a type error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:287
msgid "Shared memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:289
msgid ""
"**Shared memory** is fast on-chip memory visible to all threads within a "
"block. It is the primary tool for inter-thread communication and data reuse "
"within a block, sitting between registers (per-thread) and global memory "
"(all threads) in both speed and scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:294
msgid "Static shared memory -- `SharedArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:296
msgid "When the size is known at compile time, use `SharedArray<T, N>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:298
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, thread, SharedArray, DisjointSlice};\n"
"\n"
"static mut TILE: SharedArray<f32, 256> = SharedArray::UNINIT;\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn smem_example(input: &[f32], mut out: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    let tid = thread::threadIdx_x() as usize;\n"
"\n"
"    // Load from global to shared\n"
"    unsafe { TILE[tid] = input[idx.get()]; }\n"
"    thread::sync_threads();\n"
"\n"
"    // Read neighbor from shared (much faster than global)\n"
"    let neighbor = if tid > 0 {\n"
"        unsafe { TILE[tid - 1] }\n"
"    } else {\n"
"        0.0\n"
"    };\n"
"    thread::sync_threads();\n"
"\n"
"    if let Some(out_elem) = out.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"        *out_elem = unsafe { TILE[tid] } + neighbor;\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:326
msgid ""
"Each `static mut SharedArray` maps to a separate `.shared` allocation in "
"PTX. The `sync_threads()` barrier ensures all threads have finished writing "
"before any thread reads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:330
msgid "Dynamic shared memory -- `DynamicSharedArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:332
msgid ""
"When the size depends on runtime parameters, use `DynamicSharedArray<T>` and "
"specify the allocation size via `LaunchConfig::shared_mem_bytes`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:335
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, thread, DynamicSharedArray, DisjointSlice};\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn dynamic_smem_example(input: &[f32], mut out: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let smem = DynamicSharedArray::<f32>::get();\n"
"    let tid = thread::threadIdx_x() as usize;\n"
"\n"
"    unsafe { *smem.add(tid) = input[thread::index_1d().get()]; }\n"
"    thread::sync_threads();\n"
"    // ... use smem ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

