msgid ""
"cuda-oxide primarily uses **explicit copies** (`DeviceBuffer`, `DeviceBox`) "
"for bulk data and **HMM** for non-move closure captures and small "
"configuration data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:415
msgid "Unified Memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:417
msgid ""
"Unified Memory is CUDA's managed-memory allocator (`cudaMallocManaged`). The "
"resulting pointer is valid on both the CPU and GPU -- the CUDA runtime "
"tracks which processor \"owns\" each page and migrates it on demand. When "
"the GPU accesses a page that currently resides in host DRAM, the runtime "
"transparently copies it to device memory before the kernel reads the data. "
"This migration is invisible to your code but not free: the first access from "
"the \"wrong\" side incurs a page fault and a DMA transfer over the "
"interconnect. Subsequent accesses to the same page hit the GPU's local cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:426
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide does not currently wrap `cudaMallocManaged` directly. For "
"managed- memory workflows you would use the CUDA driver API through raw "
"bindings. In practice, `DeviceBuffer::from_host` (explicit copy) covers most "
"use cases and gives predictable performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:431
msgid "HMM (Heterogeneous Memory Management)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:433
msgid ""
"HMM is a Linux kernel feature that extends Unified Memory's demand-paging "
"model to **all system memory** -- heap allocations, `mmap` regions, and even "
"stack variables. With HMM enabled, the GPU can dereference any valid host "
"pointer without a special CUDA allocator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:438
msgid ""
"let factor = 5i32;                           // ordinary stack variable\n"
"let scale = |x: i32| x * factor;            // captures &factor (non-move)\n"
"// SAFETY: args match the kernel's signature; &factor stays alive via HMM.\n"
"unsafe { cuda_launch! { kernel: scale, args: [...] } }  // GPU reads &factor "
"via HMM\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:445
msgid ""
"Unlike Unified Memory, HMM requires no special allocation API -- the pointer "
"is a plain host address. When ATS (Address Translation Services) is "
"available on hardware-coherent platforms like Grace Hopper, it supersedes "
"HMM and provides hardware coherence at cache-line granularity; HMM is "
"automatically disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:450
msgid "What happens on a page fault"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:452
msgid ""
"When a kernel loads from an address whose page is not resident in device "
"memory, the hardware and driver cooperate to fetch it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:455
msgid "The SM executes a global load (`ld.global`) for a virtual address."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:456
msgid ""
"The **GPU MMU** looks up the address in the TLB. On a miss, it walks the "
"device page table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:458
msgid ""
"If the page table has no mapping, the GPU raises a **page fault**. The "
"faulting warp stalls; other warps on the same SM can continue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:460
msgid "The **CUDA driver fault handler** determines the source of the page:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:461
msgid ""
"*Unified Memory* -- the CUDA runtime identifies the managed allocation and "
"initiates migration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:463
msgid ""
"*HMM* -- the Linux kernel's HMM layer resolves the host virtual address, "
"pins the host page, and either migrates it or creates a remote mapping."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:465
msgid ""
"A **DMA transfer** over PCIe or NVLink copies the page from host DRAM to "
"device HBM. The GPU memory controller writes the data; the host memory "
"controller services the read."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:468
msgid ""
"The GPU page table is updated, the TLB is refilled, and the **warp "
"resumes**. The page is now local and cached in L2; subsequent accesses cost "
"only hundreds of cycles."
msgstr ""

