#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:481
msgid ""
"Because faults operate at page granularity (4 KB or 2 MB), a single fault "
"can satisfy many threads. Warp-level coalescing also helps: 32 threads "
"reading consecutive 4-byte elements touch at most one or two pages, not 32. "
"On PCIe systems, a single fault costs roughly the same as a small "
"`cudaMemcpy` -- the advantage of demand paging is that you only pay for the "
"pages you actually touch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:488
msgid "How cuda-oxide uses HMM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:490
msgid "cuda-oxide leverages HMM in two ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:492
msgid ""
"**Non-move closure captures.** When a non-`move` closure is passed to a "
"kernel, captured variables remain on the host stack and the GPU accesses "
"them through HMM pointers. This avoids copying data that the kernel only "
"reads once or infrequently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/memory-and-data-movement.md:497
msgid ""
"**Struct ABI with dynamic layout.** cuda-oxide matches Rust's actual struct "
"layout (including `#[repr(Rust)]` field reordering) on the device side, so "
"HMM-accessed host structs are read correctly without `#[repr(C)]` or manual "
"layout specification. The compiler queries `rustc` for field offsets and "
"builds matching LLVM struct types with explicit padding."
msgstr ""

